{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:10:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:10:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15396"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15396"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.05,0,0.95]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8087"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDiverticular disease of the colon is a relatively common gastrointestinal disorder. The majority of individuals with colonic diverticulosis will never have any complications, but some 10% and 25% of will experience acute diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the main risk factor for the development of this complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High calcium diet","Regular fish consumption","Regular probiotic use","Frequent aerobic exercise","Low dietary fibre intake"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EColonic diverticulosis is very common in western communities, where it affects about 70% of the population by the age of 80 years. The development of the complication of acute diverticulitis is primarily associated with lifestyle and dietary factors.   \u003Cstrong\u003ELow dietary fibre intake\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-established risk factor as it leads to increased intraluminal pressure and altered colonic motility. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular fish consumption\u003C/strong\u003E has not been shown to have any influence on the risk of diverticulitis, nor does a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh calcium diet\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EFrequent aerobic exercise\u003C/strong\u003E is actually protective against diverticulitis. \u003Cstrong\u003ERegular probiotic use\u003C/strong\u003E may have a protective effect but is not clearly linked to diverticulitis risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObesity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical inactivity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed meat consumption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertain medications (particularly non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConnective tissue disorders\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diverticulitis risk factors include low dietary fiber, obesity, physical inactivity, smoking, and certain connective tissue disorders."],"references":["Piscopo N, Ellul P. Diverticular Disease: A Review on Pathophysiology and Recent Evidence. Ulster Med J. 2020 Sep;89(2):83-88. Epub 2020 Oct 21. PMID: 33093692; PMCID: PMC7576390","Feuerstein JD, Falchuk KR. Diverticulosis and Diverticulitis. Mayo Clin Proc. 2016 Aug;91(8):1094-104. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocp.2016.03.012. Epub 2016 May 5. PMID: 27156370","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15396"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49033"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T18:17:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T18:17:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8087"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,